segments.text: Do you remember in the 70s any important proposal that you sent forward that got turned down?
No, I really don't.
Because what I always tried to do is when I went up with something, I always tried to have my P's and Q's in order and justification and all like this.
And I think that's one of the advantages.
of having the grounds report to a VP in that you have an opportunity, you live or die by what you say and what you do.
During that period did any, as far as you know, any board member or other former student or legislator or anybody get involved with second guessing any of these things?
No.
The only time
We built a driving range for Bob Ellis.
For who?
Bob Ellis, golf coach.
This was out, well, it was where the bonfire site is now.
And Bob had saved money from his golf school.
Well, I'd gotten some, arranged to get some fill to build up the tee, and he had some targets out there for more of the projects.
Anyway, Bob didn't,

it what turned out he didn't have quite enough money and we went ahead and finished up some of it out of out of my budget wasn't you know a couple thousand dollars wasn't that big a deal and then Bob I can't remember who the board member was he was from Corpus Christi I think Tony Fells yeah I think that Tony Hilton I think that's who it was maybe
Maybe not, anyway.
And so they were at some kind of a luncheon and he sat by Bob and he said, got any problems?
And Bob, I don't know whether he realized what we'd done or not, but anyway.
He said, yeah, I'm having a little problem with my driving range.
Can't seem to get anything done.
Next thing I knew, I was in Howard's office.
And I said, hey.
And I showed Howard what we'd done.
He said, well, there shouldn't be a problem.
So I went down and I talked to Bob.
And what had happened, he had mentioned some things and it was taken out of context.
And it created a little consternation.
Bob and I had a nice long, we're good friends, we had a nice long talk and it all worked out.
But that's the only time that I can ever remember that really some direct action from something from a board member got down.
Trying to think of anything else.
Did the area around the MSC board quarters
Did they require special attention?
And or that kind of courtyard?
No, that was one of what we called our Class A areas.
And we tried to, I don't think we ever

had a real problem with that area because we had, by then we'd set up what we call a garden area system where I had, and we ultimately wound up with I think 26 gardening areas on campus where that person had did everything in that given area except the large area mowing, the tree work, and this kind of thing.
And that was theirs.
And they took a lot of pride in that.
What would be some other examples?
Of gardening areas?
Well, like the central area library, we'd have probably had a gardener in each of the dormitory areas.
And what we tried to do is we did an analysis.
Now the MSC and Rudder was a little different story because we had one gardener for that area because of what it was, where it was and who was there, that kind of thing.
We had a gardener for the two residences on campus.
And like the administration building now, and a couple of buildings on either side of that, what we call the engineering block, that was broken up probably into a couple of gardeners.
But that worked very well because they knew where they were going to go every day.
And they knew that their foreman and supervisor would be checking with them, you know, if they had any problem, they needed to raise it.
And it worked extremely well.
But talking about the MSC and board quarters area, we never really had a problem with that.
I don't recall because never got any real complaints.
Oh, we might have a complaint.
We had a little litter.
and they hadn't, the gardener hadn't quite worked around, you know, or something like this, but it was usually, usually fairly minor.
I'd get a call from Bob Cherry, I guess.
President's House.
You're all responsible for gardens around there.
Yes.
Which of the president's wives was the most pleasant to work with?
I'm not going to ask the negative.
We never really had much of a problem.
Ms. Williams was usually the most outspoken, and that was because I think she was used to dealing with Bob, you know, because they had a very, very close relationship.
I don't think, I know one time when Jarvis Miller was president, he called Howard and said, they're killing my trees.
And we had several small red oaks out in

And with our water, the kind of sprinklers that we had to cover the large areas, and with particularly red oaks, and you get a summer like we've had now and you're watering a lot, you get a, what Goldwater and I call a sprinkler arc, burn for the trees.
And he said, they've done something, they're burning the leaves.
And I said, Howard, now that's not what Jarvis says.
And I said, well, in all due respect, he's wrong.
And then I got a call the next day, and he said, you've got to do something with the dang trees.
I said, Howard, I don't know what we can do.
So we went out, and I think we finally picked some leaves off the trees or something like this.
And fortunately, it started raining.
And that solved the problem.
But that's one of the only real problems that we ever had.
Which of the president's wives do you think was the most interested in the
shrubs, trees, plants, flowers.
Was there any that were particularly interested in agriculture and floriculture?
Yeah, Ms. Williams was very interested.
And, you know, Ms. Banver was to some degree
She was probably the second, I guess the second most interested, I think, but the rest of them were always usually very appreciative of what you did, you know.
Right, type is the, what I'm about to say doesn't need to go in.
It's not unusual, but I'm just sharing this as an information item.
When the Williams building

the old uh system building when it was named in honor of dr williams mrs williams was not here and the reason she wasn't here is because on thursday before the saturday dedication she was on the back porch of her house which is now glassed in changing a fluorescent bowl on a little step ladder

and she had placed it in such a fashion so she would be careful not to damage one of her orchids she had a whole bunch of okay and then leaning out to do that she fell off the little uh stepladder and broke her leg my word so horticulture had an indirect uh cause for her not to be there
in hindsight, one of the unfortunate items that day is nobody said why she couldn't be there.
They just, because each speaker thought that somebody else would explain it, or the audience, everybody knew.
Many people walked away thinking she wasn't there because she was still miffed at the campus.
That's what I thought when I read she wasn't there.
I told her about that omission later when I interviewed her, and she said, oh my, she said, I did promise Jack that I would never ever set foot on the campus again, not long before he died.
But she said, I'm beyond that now.
I've got it.
And she was here not long ago.
Oh, she was?
Yeah.
She said, I've grown up.
I've gotten better than that now.
Well, time heals.
Did you all have the responsibility for providing
flowers and so forth for various social events?
Yes.
Oh, that's got to be special.
Describe some of the pluses and minuses of those events.
There must be some that stand out.
All the building dedications and things like this.
I do remember one time we were dedicating the, what was then the new part of the Sterling Evans Library.
And I think it also fell on a Baylor football game day.
But we supplied all the podium flowers and the decorations, the greenery and everything for the stage and whatnot like that.
And so we had just gotten everything set up good.
This was probably 9 o'clock in the morning.
And Steve Hodge was out with all of his people.
They usually did the stage and set up the sound.
And we got to the point where we worked very closely with each other and learned to stay out of each other's way.

and a cold front hit with all kinds of fury, driving rain and all like this, and we had to pick everything up and move it into, and there was a huge long hallway in the building, and that's where we moved everything, and I think they ultimately had the dedication maybe there, as I recall, but I remember Jack Williamson, that's the last time we were having one outside, and that lasted for a long, long time, you know,
But, no, we did, as long as we had ample notice, where we could do the planning and all like this, there usually wasn't that much of a problem.
It was just something that we worked at and we did.
And basically because of my working with Bob and his floral background, it worked out.
We didn't have any problems.
Which president was most thoughtful in expressing appreciation for the work y'all did?
Well, I don't know.
I got nice comments from just about every president.
Uh, Jarvis Miller was always very complimentary.
Uh, Dr. Williams was complimentary too.
Uh, and Vandiver, uh, you know, they, uh, can't remember.
Oh, gosh.
No, we, we always seem to have, uh, the presence always seemed to be very, very complimentary.
of what we did.
Were there any sudden or obvious budget changes, for better or for worse?
In the early 80s, probably 80 or 81.
the coordinating board said, we're going to have to reduce the ground formulas behind him, but we'll make it up next by him.
And they cut it another 10%, you know, and it kept going.
We had a, um, and I don't remember the specific numbers, but we had a, um, and Paul, the justification line on the state budget, um,
acreage per person ratio.
And at that point in time, it was like one person per every six or seven acres.
And that has degenerated until I think now it's about one per every 15 or 16 acres.
And I'm assuming compared to all the other schools in the state,
Our ratio would have been the most extreme.
Probably, because of just the sheer area that we had.
Ours and Tech would have probably been fairly comparable.
And therefore the funding would have been less per acre.
Per acre, because we didn't have as many.
There were several ingredients.
There were linear perimeter building feet,
And they were acres of public areas, which included acreage of public and maintained areas.
That's what it was.
Streets, sidewalks, turf areas, this kind of thing.
And then there was a wage and business national survey, a wage and business multiplier that's set for the southwest area, I think.
than a student enrollment or a headcount factor in there.
And the formula, I thought, really worked pretty good.
We never got 100% of it.
The most we ever got was about 90%.
And I got to thinking in the later 80s, if we had 90% of the formula, there's not much of anything we couldn't do.
And as far as you were aware, the formula
was comparatively equitable in the way it was calculated.
Yeah.
That it did take in the appropriate factors.
Oh yeah, yeah.
When they first started, they had so many things in it that it was hard, it was just too cumbersome.
And so they brought it back down to linear perimeter feet, and I tried my best to get the Northgate wall and
and all like that.
Tom Cherry agreed with me, but they wouldn't accept it because you've got two sides to maintain, essentially a long linear building.
They kind of saw through that one, I think.
But it was worth a try.
As far as you were aware, which public four-year school in Texas, leave A&M out of the competition, which other school would you give the highest marks to for their grounds?
I don't know, it's been a while since I've been to any of them.
Tech has always done a pretty good job.
UT has
It's so crowded it's hard to say anything.
Southwest Texas does a real good job.
Allen Goldap over there I've known for years and years and years and they do a good job and I haven't been to the University of Houston in oh mercy 20 years I guess but.
All right as we go through the 80s do things get better or worse?
Oh they get
a little bit better in a sense.

We were able to get some, and I'm not sure where the money came from, some local appropriations, I guess, too, because at one point in time, in the 80s, see, we started picking up a lot of the west campus areas, you know, horticulture, medical science,
that kind of thing the and in the later 80s Easterwood Airport the terminal building there's a number of acres there that's public public areas and
We were able to, and then we had to pick up the corner markers at University in Texas and George Bush in Texas, and those add quite a bit.
And then the modular dorms came on.
All that came on about
kind of about the same time.

And one of the biggest problems we had back in the early 80s, this had to have been in 83 and 84, because we had such a monstrous coal spill in December of 83, we could not get plant material to do horticulture.
It simply wasn't available.
It had frozen.
See, we had a...
about 10 days.
No, it was about a week, I guess, that the temperature didn't get above freezing here.
And that's just terrible here.
I mean, as you well know.
Are you inferring that you all had plant material in the greenhouses you were growing?

No, we were having to buy the woody stuff, and the nurseries, you know, were, because most nurseries had gone to containers, not buckets up above the ground, and nobody was prepared for it, because the temperature started falling when we left for Christmas break that day, and it went down, and it stayed down.
far well into almost New Year's, I guess.
Well, it was cold.
But it took a while to catch up from that.
But we determined that we did a survey and inventory.
And we determined that we probably had a half million dollars of woody plant damage campus wide.
Maybe it was closer to 600,000, but it was
a lot of damaged plants.
Down through the years that you've been here, did you all attempt to grow any of your own plant material?
We grew a lot of the small stuff, the ground covers and things of this nature.
We grew all of our annuals.
I'm not sure what they do now because, well, that's been scaled back so, but all of our annuals we grew.
Where were the greenhouses?
They were out at the Henson Park grounds area.
In fact, they're still there, I think.
But, and we used to grow a few small trees in containers.
We would order what we call liners, one- and two-year-old trees, and containerize them.
And that gave us a lot of material where we had, we'd have an area that needed something and it was not very,

uh... not very costly to do that and we could put out a few you know get them up four five six feet where they could kind of defend themselves and uh... that's where a lot of the trees like that came from I know for instance the crape myrtles
that line New Main Drive coming around, we bought those as small liners and grew them for two years and bought two different groups.
We planted the first group up to the curve and then around the curve the second year.
And it took about four years to do all that.
Did anybody in a position of authority at any level ever give any indication of any favorite
or unfavorite annuals?
Grow more of these and less of those?
No, not really.
The only time we ever really had a problem is with the system or the administration building bed.
And we used to try to crop areas like that at least twice a year, sometimes three times a year.
And particularly when commencement

was a little later than what it is we could never get the pansies there and we'd have to tear them out or on some other beds on campus too you know you you you do all your planning you grow the plants and maybe you have an extended season or something like this and these are not

too bad they're still pretty good but these need to have need they they need home and oh I'd get calls why in the world are you taking out these good plants you know and I'd try to very patiently go through the explanation of why well that still doesn't make sense well you know it could turn off real hot and it'd be gone in 30 minutes you know and uh but uh that's the only only problem we've ever really had I think with annuals who made the
the specific decision of which annuals where?
That was kind of a community thing between Bill Vitapil, myself, and whoever was working under Bill in the greenhouses.
We'd sit down and we at one point in time we had all of our annual beds and we had a kind of set rotation of different crops because we tried generally never to follow
one crop was the same thing.
You know, like petunias, we would not plant those probably for two years just because of inherent disease problems that you could get.
Did you have any favorites?
Oh, yeah.
No, Janet would get it.
She's back.
What's your favorite?
Oh, I like the pansies for winter.
Calendulas are good.
I like the petunias.

they they don't stand up to the heat quite as well the periwinkles or vinca are good a real good hot weather crop but a lot of people plant them too early and they start going down on them and what what they do they get a fungal infection on stems but you don't periwinkles shouldn't be planted until probably late may early june here
because they're a lot like cotton.
They like hot weather.
But, no, there's a number of good plants.
Could we ever have done any Texas wildflowers?
Yeah, we tried to do some Texas wildflowers out on what we call the sea pasture out along Texas Avenue, and it didn't turn out very well.
We had...
I guess when Vandiver was president.
There's out there, and I think Richard Thornton, who preceded me in the grounds area in the early 60s, Richard and I were classmates at Tech, but he had planted some islands of trees out there.
Some of the crape myrtles came from the Riverside campus, the old annex, and they planted them out in that open area.
And when we were trying to scrape up manpower to go west and handle horticulture and places like that, well, I talked to, I guess it might have been Chuck Cargill at the time.
He might have been my boss in it, either he or Howard.
And said, you know, I need to try to gain some mowing time at least.
So we laid out some areas where those tree islands are that we didn't mow.
We mowed them a couple of tree times a year.
And that gave us enough manpower to go out and mow around horticulture and places like that.
And in that, we tried to do some wildflowers.
And at that point in time, we weren't that familiar with them.
And we got a few going, but we didn't get enough soil
contact and then when the the terminal
uh, Eastwood terminal came in, we thought about doing some out there and I couldn't get permission.
Nobody said, no, we don't want to do that.
You know, and I kept saying, well, this might be appropriate, you know, and, and I wanted to do something again on the sea pasture because I think that would be very appropriate.
And of course, Bob Ellis now has his driving range out there where I wanted to do a lot of that.
But, um, they were afraid of the, um,

see how the the rattiness that it might look you know what when it's going down I said people look at the roadsides they understand that you wait until they seed you mow them you know and you go on I said it would save us a lot of money but I never could and by then it was Robert Smith and that didn't fly right uh

in terms of the let's go through the the vice presidents uh you first reported bob cherry tom cherry i mean tom cherry tom cherry uh clyde freeman hired vestal and vestal served till about when well let's see they vandiver split the job oh okay so this so

and and then Cargill picked up the what they call it operations maybe or okay so you reported then to Chuck Cargill yeah did your title and responsibilities change no just what they did they took Chuck wound up with grounds physical plant
University Police, the airport, and there was probably one other.
No, that's about it.
And then Howard kept the fiscal area, personnel, the auxiliaries, you know, that was kind of a split on it.
What was Chuck Kergel's management style?
Chuck was one of those that when he knew something, you knew it.
And Joe Esterly, who was director of physical at the time, used to kid him for having Teflon overcoat because nothing stuck to that guy.
You know, I like Chuck.
Chuck's a good friend.
But, I mean, any time he found out something, either Joe or I or Bob White,
or all of us found out about it, depending on where the impetus went, you know, of the need.
And he used to always say, he said, you guys do such a good job.
I said, boy, you're just, you know, I don't know what I'd do without you.
And, you know, we had a great relationship, really.
I mean, because he went, I mean, the minute he found out something, you knew it.
Who followed you?
Robert Smith.

his style was one of everything was close to the vest and Robert didn't tell you anything that he didn't think he didn't perceive you might need to know period that's just the way he was and going from Cargill to Robert Smith was really a shock yeah back in the late in the early 70s when I was

first dean of faculty was the associate vice president of academic affairs and I remember one day we had a session at the working level with Robert Smith and Dick said when he dies they're gonna have to hire pallbearers so then so you reported to Robert throughout his
Robert took over in 87, I think.
And then, I guess in probably early, late 89, Robert replaced Joe Estrill.
He and Joe got into something, I don't know.
I'm not sure what it was.
I know they had some, they would have some strong discussions on staff meeting, you know.
But anyway, and then suddenly he moved Joe to associate director for utilities.
And then early in 90, a guy by the name of Joe Sugg appeared.
Sugg, S-U-G-G. Joe was an Air Force colonel, retired.
And
had
